GIF Inline Rendering Fix Plan

Objective

Make pasted or uploaded animated GIFs render as animated media in chat, rather than flattening to the first frame.

Architecture change

Separate media handling into three distinct objects:
	•	original asset
	•	preview asset
	•	render policy

Right now the likely failure is that preview generation is overwriting or replacing the original asset for display.

Required pipeline

1. Ingestion
When a user pastes or uploads media:
	•	inspect MIME type
	•	inspect file signature, not just extension
	•	detect animation by checking:
	•	GIF multi-frame structure
	•	animated WebP chunks
	•	loopable short video formats if supported

Output:

{
  "asset_type": "animated_image",
  "mime": "image/gif",
  "is_animated": true,
  "source_preserved": true
}

2. Asset preservation
Store:
	•	original GIF binary untouched
	•	lightweight poster frame separately

Rule:
poster frame may never replace original asset for render path selection

3. Composer preview
Before sending, show a visible badge:
	•	GIF
	•	Animated

If flattening occurred, show:
	•	Static preview only

That gives immediate user feedback.

4. Message renderer
Renderer decision tree:
	•	if is_animated == true
	•	use animated media renderer
	•	else
	•	use static image renderer

Do not route animated media through the generic image component.

5. Playback behavior
Default:
	•	autoplay when visible
	•	pause when offscreen
	•	loop while onscreen

Fallback:
	•	reduced motion enabled → still image + play button
	•	low power mode → tap to play
	•	oversized asset → optimized playback surrogate

6. Optimization path
Large GIFs are inefficient.

So:
	•	preserve original GIF
	•	generate looping MP4/WebM surrogate for playback
	•	use surrogate for inline rendering
	•	keep original for export/open/download

That gives:
	•	lower memory
	•	smoother playback
	•	less battery drain

